// C2: Acting Components
instance AxisController : DTDFVocab:ActingComponent [
    base:desc "Siemens SINUMERIK 840D sl controller managing motion control and real-time data acquisition for the first vertical axis of MABI MAX 100 robot, enabling automated data flow to the Digital Shadow."
]

instance MotionControlSystem : DTDFVocab:ActingComponent [
    base:desc "High-level motion control system integrating controller commands and feedback for multi-physics aware monitoring of joint dynamics in the robot's first axis."
]

// C3: Physical sensing components
instance AxisCurrentSensor : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "Current sensor capturing electrical current measurements from the motor driving the first vertical axis of MABI MAX 100 robot for friction identification analysis."
    DTDFVocab:producedData AxisCurrentDataTransmitted
]

instance AxisTorqueSensor : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "Torque sensor measuring mechanical torque transmitted through the gearbox of the first vertical axis for dynamic behavior monitoring."
    DTDFVocab:producedData AxisTorqueDataTransmitted
]

instance AxisVelocitySensor : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "Angular velocity sensor capturing rotational speed data of the first vertical axis to support multi-physics simulation and friction analysis."
    DTDFVocab:producedData AxisVelocityDataTransmitted
]

// C4: Physical-to-virtual interaction
instance AxisCurrentDataTransmitted : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom AxisCurrentSensor
]

instance AxisTorqueDataTransmitted : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom AxisTorqueSensor
]

instance AxisVelocityDataTransmitted : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom AxisVelocitySensor
]

// C10: Models/Data
instance FrictionIdentificationModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Behavioral model developed using SysML IBDs and Simulink for analyzing friction characteristics in the mechanical system of the first vertical axis, incorporating multi-physics simulations."
]

instance AxisDynamicBehaviorModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Logical architecture model describing the dynamic behavior of the first vertical axis using AADL and MontiArc Automaton for component-connector relationships and state transitions."
]

instance AxisCurrentData : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Aggregated current measurement data transmitted via MQTT from the physical axis to the Digital Shadow for contextual analysis and abstraction."
    DTDFVocab:fromData AxisCurrentDataTransmitted
]

instance AxisTorqueData : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Processed torque measurement data collected in real-time from the gearbox system for multi-physics aware monitoring of the first vertical axis."
    DTDFVocab:fromData AxisTorqueDataTransmitted
]

instance AxisVelocityData : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Rotational velocity data captured from the axis encoder system, transmitted via MQTT for integration into the Digital Shadow's contextual data traces."
    DTDFVocab:fromData AxisVelocityDataTransmitted
]

// C11: Enablers
instance DataAggregationEnabler : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "MQTT-based data aggregation pipeline processing real-time sensor data streams from the physical axis into structured digital representations for the Digital Shadow."
    DTDFVocab:enables DataCollectionService
]

instance SimulationEnabler : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "MathWorks Simulink environment enabling multi-physics simulations of the first vertical axis dynamics using the aggregated sensor data and behavioral models."
    DTDFVocab:enables SimulationService
]

instance DataProcessingEnabler : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "C++/Java-based data processing pipeline implementing custom algorithms for preprocessing and abstraction of sensor data traces collected from the physical system."
    DTDFVocab:enables DataProcessingService
]

instance ControlIntegrationEnabler : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Interface layer integrating controller commands from SINUMERIK 840D sl with the Digital Shadow's logical architecture models for coordinated behavior analysis."
    DTDFVocab:enables ControlIntegrationService
]

// C6: Services
instance DataCollectionService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Passive data collection service aggregating one-way sensor data streams from the physical axis to the Digital Shadow without bidirectional control capabilities."
    DTDFVocab:provides AxisCurrentInsight, AxisTorqueInsight
]

instance ContextualizationService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Contextual data abstraction service processing raw sensor measurements into meaningful traces for specific monitoring purposes within the Digital Shadow."
    DTDFVocab:provides FrictionPatternInsight, DynamicBehaviorInsight
]

instance SimulationService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Multi-physics simulation service executing behavioral models using aggregated sensor data to predict and analyze axis dynamics in real-time."
    DTDFVocab:provides SimulationResultInsight, PerformanceMetricInsight
]

instance FrictionAnalysisService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Friction identification service analyzing current and torque data traces to characterize mechanical friction in the axis system using the Digital Shadow's models."
    DTDFVocab:provides FrictionCoefficientInsight, WearPredictionInsight
]

instance DataProcessingService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Data preprocessing service implementing custom algorithms for transforming raw sensor data into structured formats for analysis."
    DTDFVocab:provides ProcessedDataInsight
]

instance ControlIntegrationService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Control integration service coordinating between physical controller commands and digital shadow models for behavior analysis."
    DTDFVocab:provides ControlAnalysisInsight
]

// C17: Insights/Actions
instance AxisCurrentInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Real-time insight into electrical current characteristics of the first vertical axis motor, derived from processed sensor data for monitoring purposes."
]

instance AxisTorqueInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Mechanical torque analysis insight providing understanding of load conditions on the gearbox system through processed data traces."
]

instance FrictionPatternInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Contextual insight into friction patterns identified through aggregated sensor data and behavioral models for predictive maintenance."
]

instance DynamicBehaviorInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Logical architecture insight describing the dynamic behavior of the axis system based on processed data and simulation results."
]

instance FrictionCoefficientInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Quantitative insight into friction coefficient characteristics derived from current and torque data analysis within the Digital Shadow."
]

instance WearPredictionInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Predictive insight into potential wear patterns in the mechanical components based on friction analysis and dynamic behavior modeling."
]

instance SimulationResultInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Simulation results insight providing analysis of axis dynamics based on multi-physics simulations."
]

instance PerformanceMetricInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Performance metrics insight analyzing operational characteristics of the axis system."
]

instance ProcessedDataInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Insight into processed sensor data formats and quality metrics for analysis purposes."
]

instance ControlAnalysisInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Analysis of control system behavior and its integration with digital shadow models."
]

// C12: Environment
instance RobotAxisEnvironment : DTDFVocab:Environment [
    base:desc "Operational environment containing the first vertical axis components and their interactions within the MABI MAX 100 robot system."
    base:contains AxisMotorComponent, AxisGearboxComponent, AxisController
]

instance AxisMotorComponent : DTDFVocab:Component [
    base:desc "Mechanical motor component driving the first vertical axis of the MABI MAX 100 robot, interfaced with current and velocity sensors for dynamic monitoring."
    base:isContainedIn RobotAxisEnvironment
]

instance AxisGearboxComponent : DTDFVocab:Component [
    base:desc "Mechanical gearbox system transmitting power from the motor to the axis, equipped with torque sensors for load monitoring and dynamic behavior analysis."
    base:isContainedIn RobotAxisEnvironment
]

// C10: Additional Relationships
instance FrictionIdentificationModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    DTDFVocab:inputTo DataAggregationEnabler, SimulationEnabler
]

instance AxisDynamicBehaviorModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    DTDFVocab:inputTo DataProcessingEnabler, ControlIntegrationEnabler
]

instance AxisCurrentData : DTDFVocab:Data [
    DTDFVocab:inputTo DataAggregationEnabler
]

instance AxisTorqueData : DTDFVocab:Data [
    DTDFVocab:inputTo DataAggregationEnabler
]

instance AxisVelocityData : DTDFVocab:Data [
    DTDFVocab:inputTo DataAggregationEnabler
]

// Added missing SystemUnderStudy instance
instance FrictionShadow : DTDFVocab:SystemUnderStudy [
    base:desc "Digital Shadow for the first vertical axis of MABI MAX 100 robot focusing on friction identification and dynamic behavior analysis."
    DTDFVocab:hasEnvironment RobotAxisEnvironment
]

instance twinning_time_scale : DTDFVocab:TimeScale [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system described in the provided documents operates within a **real-time, data-driven temporal framework**, where sensor data (e.g., friction measurements) is **streamed via MQTT** for continuous monitoring of the physical system's state. The system emphasizes **low-latency synchronization** between the physical object (e.g., a robot's axis) and its digital representation, ensuring near-instantaneous updates to the Digital Shadow (e.g., *FrictionShadow*). While the document does not explicitly quantify synchronization frequencies or latency requirements, the **one-way data flow** (as per Kritzinger et al. [32]) implies reliance on **live, streaming data** rather than batch processing or discrete time steps. The integration of simulation tools (e.g., MathWorks Simulink) suggests support for **configurable time scales** in behavioral modeling, though specific granularity (e.g., event-driven vs. fixed-step) is not detailed. The overall approach aligns with **real-time, data-driven representations** of physical systems, prioritizing temporal alignment for operational decision-making."
]

instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system’s orchestration follows **architecture-centric patterns** rooted in **Model-Based Systems Engineering (MBSE)**, leveraging **architecture description languages (ADLs)** like **SysML IBDs [17], AADL [24], or MontiArc [25]–[26]** to define **component-connector structures**, interfaces, and compositions. **Resource management** is implicitly handled via **tool-specific frameworks** (e.g., Simulink [28] for simulation, general-purpose languages like C++/Java for behavior) and **heterogeneous stakeholder integration** (as per [31]). System-wide coordination is achieved through **multi-layered abstraction** (e.g., RFLP [18] or OOSEM [20]), where **functional/logical architectures** (described via ADLs) are linked to **physical/technical layers** via **behavioral models** (e.g., state machines in SysML v1.7 or MontiArc Automaton). No explicit **orchestration frameworks** (e.g., Kubernetes, service meshes) or **real-time coordination protocols** (e.g., DDS, ROS) are mentioned; instead, coordination relies on **model-driven integration** of disparate tools and notations. The **Digital Shadow Reference Model [32]** further implies **passive data aggregation** with **active interpretation layers** (e.g., [35]–[37]) as the primary coordination mechanism."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "
The Digital Twin system addresses **fidelity and validity** through:
- **Model Fidelity Requirements**: Fidelity is ensured via **abstraction layers** (e.g., RFLP methodology) to manage complexity, where models are progressively refined from **requirements → functional → logical → physical layers**. Higher abstraction layers (e.g., logical) may abstract away low-level details to simplify analysis.
- **Validation and Verification Methods**: Behavioral models are validated using **simulation tools like Simulink** and other modeling environments to test system responses under defined conditions. Cross-tool consistency checks are implied to align models across heterogeneous representations (e.g., SysML, AADL, Simulink).
- **Uncertainty Sources**: Increased model complexity introduces **parameter determination challenges**, potentially leading to uncertainties (e.g., wear, environmental factors). These are mitigated through **active components** that process and interpret sensor data to refine model accuracy.
- **Error Detection and Correction Mechanisms**: While not explicitly detailed, the reliance on **active components** suggests mechanisms for real-time error detection (e.g., via anomaly detection in streaming data) and correction (e.g., model recalibration).
- **Quality Assurance Processes**: Quality is ensured through **integrated stakeholder perspectives** and **methodological rigor** in MBSE, though specific protocols (e.g., formal verification, statistical validation) are not described.
"
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "The technical network infrastructure for the Digital Shadow system is described implicitly through the **MQTT protocol** for data streaming between physical objects and digital representations. No explicit details regarding network topology, bandwidth requirements, redundancy mechanisms, or security protocols are provided in the document. The system does not explicitly mention bidirectional control flows or command execution mechanisms, as the Digital Shadow reference model emphasizes a **one-way data flow** from physical to digital. Therefore, no technical connection specifics beyond MQTT-based communication are available."
]

instance dt_hosting_deployment : DTDFVocab:Deployment [
    base:desc "The deployment infrastructure for the Digital Shadow system is not explicitly detailed in the provided documents. The text mentions **visualization in a dashboard** and the use of **MathWorks Simulink** for modeling, but no specific hosting platforms (cloud/edge/on-premise), computational/storage requirements, scalability mechanisms, or deployment models are referenced. The document does not provide information on availability/reliability assurance or the use of any deployment tools."
]

instance horizontal_integration : DTDFVocab:HoriIntegration [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system’s horizontal integration is constrained to **sensor-to-digital data streaming via MQTT**, enabling real-time communication between physical sensors (e.g., friction sensors) and the Digital Shadow (*FrictionShadow*). The document does not mention broader **interoperability standards** (e.g., OPC UA, DDS) or **enterprise system dependencies**, focusing instead on the **local integration** with the robot’s controller (Siemens SINUMERIK 840D sl). While **architecture description languages (ADLs)** like SysML IBDs and AADL define **standardized component interfaces**, the integration patterns are limited to **sensor-controller-digital shadow pipelines** without explicit references to **legacy system compatibility** or **cross-system data exchange protocols**. The absence of broader enterprise integration suggests a **domain-specific focus** on manufacturing automation rather than multi-system interoperability."
]

instance standardization : DTDFVocab:Standardization [
    base:desc "The document references the use of standardized modeling languages and methodologies for Digital Twin development, including SysML (Systems Modeling Language) and Architecture Description Languages (ADLs) such as ACME, AADL, and MontiArc. These standards are employed to describe functional and logical architectures, component interfaces, and system behavior. The document also mentions the use of SysML v1.7 state machines and MontiArc Automaton for behavioral modeling. However, no explicit mention is made of broader industry standards (e.g., ISO/IEC, IEEE P2414) or certification frameworks, nor does it detail interoperability standards beyond the mentioned ADLs."
]

instance security_and_safety_considerations : DTDFVocab:SecuritySafety [
    base:desc "
The Digital Twin system described in the provided documents incorporates **safety-critical physical constraints** through a **safety cell** (as referenced in [44] MABI robotic arm documentation), which physically restricts the operational workspace of the robotic system to predefined boundaries. This ensures **collision avoidance** and **operator safety** by limiting the robot's motion to a monitored area.

In the context of **model-driven engineering for Digital Twins in manufacturing** ([43]), the system emphasizes **traceability** of data to its origin, ensuring that all digital representations remain **fully traceable** to physical assets. However, explicit **cybersecurity protocols**, **access control mechanisms**, or **authentication systems** are not detailed in the provided documents. The **Asset Administration Shell (AAS)** framework ([46], [47], [50]) does not explicitly address data ownership or privacy measures, focusing instead on **semantic interoperability** and **data modeling** for industrial assets.

No references to **ISO 26262**, **IEC 62443**, or **role-based access control (RBAC)** are present in the documents, and no **threat mitigation strategies** or **fail-safe mechanisms** beyond physical safety cells are mentioned. The provided context does not include **data anonymization**, **consent management**, or **compliance with data protection regulations** (e.g., GDPR)."
]